[2] Viet Nam
Date: 12 Sep 2004
From: ProMED-mail <promed@promedmail.org>
Source: Xinhua News Agency, 7 Sep 2004 [edited]
<http://www.xinhuanet.com/english/index.htm>

Dengue fever in Viet Nam, which has eased off since August 2004, killed 73
local people in the first 8 months of this year [2004], a higher number than
the total number of deaths caused by the mosquito-borne disease last year
[2003].
The country detected some 1500 new dengue fever patients in each week
of August and in early September 2004, down 100 percent [sic] compared with
the previous peak months, the local newspaper Pioneer, on Tue 7 Sep
2004, quoted the Preventive Medicine Department, under the Ministry
of Health, as saying. Nearly 45 830 local people nationwide were
reported to have suffered from dengue fever between January and early
September 2004, mostly from southern localities such as the provinces
of Soc Trang, Bac Lieu, and Ben Tre, whose weather is most favorable
for the development of mosquitoes.
In an effort to minimize the number of new infections, the ministry
has recently launched an urgent nationwide program on dengue fever
prevention, supplied localities with more mosquito-killing chemicals,
medicines, and equipment, and, called for local health agencies to
raise public awareness of the disease.
Specifically, all residents across Viet Nam are urged to focus on
killing mosquitoes and their larvae on each Friday. The country is
spending 18 billion Vietnamese dong (USD 1.1 million) on anti-dengue
fever activities this year [2004].
In 2003, Viet Nam reported 35 073 cases of dengue fever infection, including
58 fatalities -- dengue cases up 48 percent & fatalities up 45 percent from
2002.
--
ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>
