[3] Australia (Queensland): outbreak over
Date: 12 Sep 2004
From: ProMED-mail <promed@promedmail.org>
Source: Townsville, 8 Sep 2004 [edited]
<http://www.townsvilleonline.com.au/>

The dengue fever outbreak in the twin cities was officially declared
over this week [1st week of September 2004], after no new cases were
reported for the past 3 months.
The Tropical Public Health Unit, and the Townsville City Council,
declared the outbreak to be officially over on Monday [6 Sep 2004].
The outbreak began in Cranbrook in October [2003] and saw 58
confirmed dengue fever cases. The Tropical Public Health Unit
Director of Environmental Health Services, John Piispanen, said some
old lessons have been revised throughout the dengue fever outbreak
including ways to motivate people to check for breeding sites around
their homes.
He said the inspections of North Ward showed the importance of
regularly checking key containers, such as disused septic tanks and
wells, which provide prolific dengue mosquito breeding sites.
"This year's [2004] dengue outbreak in Townsville began when a person
who had contracted the dengue virus overseas, most probably in Papua
New Guinea, came into contact with local dengue mosquitoes, which
then spread the virus to local residents," Mr. Piispanen said.
Councillor Jenny Hill said Townsville City Council worked closely
with mosquito control experts from the Tropical Public Health Unit to
conduct house-to-house inspections and mosquito eradication. More
than 1000 premises were inspected, mostly in Cranbrook, Currajong,
and North Ward.
Mr. Piispanen said the outbreak proved that dengue fever doesn't just
follow the wet season, but, that there is a higher risk then.
A wide variety of levels of illness from dengue fever were shown
during the outbreak, with some people showing very few symptoms on
the one hand, to the death from dengue fever in the Torres Strait
Islands on the other, according to Mr. Piispanen.
[Byline: Kerri-Anne Mesner]
